gonna start to lose funding.

52
00:02:43,597 --> 00:02:46,465
Okay, yeah.
Well, think about it.

53
00:02:46,566 --> 00:02:50,401
Otherwise I'm gonna have to
give my friend Earl, here, a sad face.

54
00:02:57,644 --> 00:03:01,581
Uh, was that our medical director
attached to an IV of cis-platinum?

55
00:03:01,648 --> 00:03:03,310
Don't ask.

56
00:03:03,750 --> 00:03:05,116
Why are you here?

57
00:03:05,285 --> 00:03:06,583
Uh, tough one.

58
00:03:06,653 --> 00:03:09,282
Uh, because this is a
hospital and I'm a doctor.

59
00:03:09,923 --> 00:03:12,825
You said that you were
gonna take some time off.

60
00:03:12,993 --> 00:03:14,325
Well, that was before.

61
00:03:14,428 --> 00:03:17,455
I mean, Max needs
my help, clearly.

62
00:03:17,931 --> 00:03:20,400
Sweetheart, this is important.

63
00:03:20,467 --> 00:03:21,935
You need to take
care of yourself.

64
00:03:22,002 --> 00:03:24,301
And I am going to, okay.

65
00:03:24,604 --> 00:03:27,005
I'm just gonna do it
without leaving the hospital.

66
00:03:27,941 --> 00:03:29,739
I flushed all my
pills this morning.

67
00:03:29,810 --> 00:03:31,642
You know I'm going cold turkey?

68
00:03:31,745 --> 00:03:33,907
Yes, it is gonna
suck for a while,

69
00:03:33,980 --> 00:03:36,472
but it's what I need to
do. And not just for me.

70
00:03:36,583 --> 00:03:37,607
For Max.

71
00:03:38,118 --> 00:03:39,245
Oh.

72
00:03:39,586 --> 00:03:41,350
Ooh, triage. Gotta run.

73
00:03:51,331 --> 00:03:52,492
Damn it, Andy.

74
00:03:52,599 --> 00:03:54,534
Triage said an acute
coronary syndrome in here.

75
00:03:54,634 --> 00:03:57,502
I did not use those words
'cause I don't know them,

76
00:03:57,604 --> 00:03:59,266
but it had to sound serious

77
00:03:59,339 --> 00:04:01,117
or they would have given
me to one of your residents.

78
00:04:01,141 --> 00:04:04,270
Yeah, well, you nearly
gave me an acute coronary.

79
00:04:04,544 --> 00:04:06,479
Did you do something
new with your hair?

80
00:04:06,546 --> 00:04:08,186
All right, Andy,
what's the story?

81
00:04:08,281 --> 00:04:10,113
My knee's been swelling up.

82
00:04:10,517 --> 00:04:12,213
I can't move it without...

83
00:04:12,819 --> 00:04:15,653
Patel, let's, uh, let's
drain Andy's knee.

84
00:04:15,722 --> 00:04:17,350
Hey, take your time, LB.

85
00:04:17,524 --> 00:04:18,958
Clean sheets.

86
00:04:27,501 --> 00:04:30,403
Tony, I know it's difficult
to talk about the attack but

87
00:04:31,538 --> 00:04:33,166
you should.

88
00:04:39,513 --> 00:04:42,176
I was painting up in Mohonk.

89
00:04:43,216 --> 00:04:44,912
Lots of light.

90
00:04:45,719 --> 00:04:49,053
My dad came with
me, so I was annoyed.

91
00:04:49,389 --> 00:04:50,982
I'd wanted to go solo.

92
00:04:52,325 --> 00:04:54,317
But it's good he was there,

93
00:04:54,394 --> 00:04:57,421
'cause when I moved my
easel near the tree line, I...

94
00:04:58,431 --> 00:04:59,490
I saw this shape.

95
00:05:00,867 --> 00:05:03,530
Okay. Tell me more about that.

96
00:05:04,237 --> 00:05:05,933
It was daytime.

97
00:05:06,506 --> 00:05:08,907
They're nocturnal, right?

98
00:05:09,209 --> 00:05:10,233
Yeah.

99
00:05:11,011 --> 00:05:12,445
It shouldn't have been there.

100
00:05:15,348 --> 00:05:17,442
But I saw it, and it just...

101
00:05:17,551 --> 00:05:19,281
it just stared at me.

102
00:05:19,686 --> 00:05:20,949
Mmm.

103
00:05:21,288 --> 00:05:23,348
And then it started running

104
00:05:23,423 --> 00:05:25,415
right at me

105
00:05:25,525 --> 00:05:28,290
and then I turned
and ran, and I'm fast.

106
00:05:28,562 --> 00:05:31,862
I used to run track, but
I didn't make it two feet.

107
00:05:33,233 --> 00:05:35,031
Before it... Before...

108
00:05:38,371 --> 00:05:39,771
So...

109
00:05:40,106 --> 00:05:43,076
before this most recent
attack, you hadn't seen the wolf

110
00:05:43,143 --> 00:05:44,975
in over a month, correct?

111
00:05:45,979 --> 00:05:47,277
Uh...

112
00:05:50,217 --> 00:05:51,549
Yeah.

113
00:05:54,287 --> 00:05:56,882
Hey, Tony, is the, um...

114
00:05:57,657 --> 00:05:59,956
is the wolf here right now?

115
00:06:14,441 --> 00:06:16,433
Okay, all right. Here's
what we're gonna do.

116
00:06:16,509 --> 00:06:20,605
I am gonna go get your dad,
and we are going to talk next steps.

117
00:06:21,147 --> 00:06:22,581
Okay?

118
00:06:23,183 --> 00:06:24,776
Right. Okay.

119
00:06:35,128 --> 00:06:36,926
Oh, my God, this is Rohan.

120
00:06:36,997 --> 00:06:40,934
I mean, I thought it might be because
he has the same... but I didn't wanna...

121
00:06:41,001 --> 00:06:42,333
okay, I'm done.

122
00:06:42,435 --> 00:06:44,995
Hi. Hi. Oh, it's so
nice to meet you.

123
00:06:45,105 --> 00:06:47,870
Your dad talks about
you all the time. He does?

124
00:06:48,108 --> 00:06:50,805
Okay, thank you.
Thank you, Ella.

125
00:06:50,877 --> 00:06:53,437
Now he's blushing,
so this is a disaster.

126
00:06:53,513 --> 00:06:56,608
I'm gonna go, but I
hope I see you again.

127
00:06:59,653 --> 00:07:01,212
You talk about me?

128
00:07:01,821 --> 00:07:05,986
Uh, yes. I wanted to get you a
gift, and Ella was helping me.

129
00:07:06,059 --> 00:07:07,322
What kind of gift?

130
00:07:07,394 --> 00:07:08,623
We've not decided,

131
00:07:08,695 --> 00:07:11,007
but I didn't want to get you
something which meant something

132
00:07:11,031 --> 00:07:13,364
other than what I
wanted it to mean.

133
00:07:13,466 --> 00:07:15,458
Oh, that's...

134
00:07:15,535 --> 00:07:17,197
that's thoughtful.

135
00:07:18,538 --> 00:07:20,905
There is something...
Yes, tell me.

136
00:07:21,408 --> 00:07:23,309
I told you about the songs
I'm writing? Mmm-hmm.

137
00:07:23,410 --> 00:07:24,810
Well, I'd love to make a demo,

138
00:07:24,878 --> 00:07:27,814
and to do that, I
need to rent a studio.

139
00:07:28,915 --> 00:07:31,384
I was wondering if
you could, you know...

140
00:07:31,484 --> 00:07:32,850
Give you money?

141
00:07:34,921 --> 00:07:37,652
I don't think it's a good idea.

142
00:07:39,159 --> 00:07:42,527
Okay. Okay. Baby steps, right?

143
00:07:50,270 --> 00:07:52,330
LB. How's that knee doing?

144
00:07:52,505 --> 00:07:54,030
It's better. Oh.

145
00:07:54,107 --> 00:07:55,268
So why are you still here?

146
00:07:55,375 --> 00:07:57,344
I meant better than bad,

147
00:07:57,410 --> 00:07:58,935
which is still, you
know, not good.

148
00:07:59,045 --> 00:08:02,015
All right, Andy. Why don't you
tell me what's really going on?

149
00:08:04,851 --> 00:08:08,219
My shelter voucher
doesn't start till Saturday,

150
00:08:08,288 --> 00:08:09,722
so I got four
days on the street.

151
00:08:09,789 --> 00:08:11,223
So I thought...

152
00:08:11,291 --> 00:08:12,782
We're a hospital, okay?

153
00:08:12,892 --> 00:08:15,361
You don't warrant
an overnight stay. Yet.

154
00:08:15,428 --> 00:08:16,794
Just do some more digging.

155
00:08:16,896 --> 00:08:21,095
There's gotta be something else wrong
with me. I'm a very unhealthy person.

156
00:08:21,201 --> 00:08:22,567
You paged?

157
00:08:22,635 --> 00:08:23,694
Uh, yeah.

158
00:08:23,770 --> 00:08:26,137
Yeah, is, uh, now a bad time?

159
00:08:26,239 --> 00:08:27,434
For both of you?

160
00:08:27,540 --> 00:08:28,906
Oh, yeah. What do you got?

161
00:08:28,975 --> 00:08:31,615
You said you wanted to know the
next time a frequent flyer came in.

162
00:08:31,644 --> 00:08:33,556
Yeah, frequent flyers
mean we're not doing our job.

163
00:08:33,580 --> 00:08:34,878
Oh, well, then you're in luck.

164
00:08:34,948 --> 00:08:37,713
Meet the Amelia
Earhart of frequent flyers,

165
00:08:37,784 --> 00:08:39,047
Andy Keener.

166
00:08:42,722 --> 00:08:44,088
How can I help?

167
00:08:44,391 --> 00:08:46,553
Looking good, Dr. Reynolds.

168
00:08:46,626 --> 00:08:47,889
Just hold it there.

169
00:08:48,595 --> 00:08:49,756
Fantastic.

170
00:08:49,829 --> 00:08:51,627
That's perfect. Thanks, Chris.

171
00:08:51,831 --> 00:08:53,231
That was great.

172
00:08:53,299 --> 00:08:55,165
This is going to come
together seamlessly.

173
00:08:55,268 --> 00:08:59,103
I thought Fred Niemens usually
does the, uh, medical articles?

174
00:08:59,172 --> 00:09:03,906
My editor thought the personal angle
would be better for The Face of Diversity.

175
00:09:03,977 --> 00:09:05,275
Is that the angle?

176
00:09:05,345 --> 00:09:07,109
I figured we'd start
with a profile on you

177
00:09:07,180 --> 00:09:09,540
and then talk about how you've
put together your department.

178
00:09:09,783 --> 00:09:11,752
Okay. For your
profile, I was thinking

179
00:09:11,818 --> 00:09:13,018
it's a "rags to riches" story.

180
00:09:13,119 --> 00:09:14,348
I already know the layout.

181
00:09:14,687 --> 00:09:16,932
Just below the headline, there'll
be these two pictures of you

182
00:09:16,956 --> 00:09:18,254
where you are now

183
00:09:19,025 --> 00:09:20,516
right next to this.

184
00:09:24,297 --> 00:09:26,442
I wanna know the details of what
led to the mug shot, so we can...

185
00:09:26,466 --> 00:09:27,798
This interview is over.

186
00:09:27,867 --> 00:09:29,096
Wait.

187
00:09:33,540 --> 00:09:36,476
Um, sorry, I didn't mean...

188
00:09:44,117 --> 00:09:46,279
Your chemo bag is
making people nervous.

189
00:09:46,352 --> 00:09:48,617
Yeah, sorry, just one more hour.

190
00:09:48,688 --> 00:09:50,623
And by "people," I mean me.

191
00:09:50,824 --> 00:09:54,317
Did you know that Andy Keener has
been in this hospital over 100 times?

192
00:09:54,394 --> 00:09:56,056
He's a frequent flyer.

193
00:09:56,162 --> 00:09:57,840
If my math is correct,
and I'm pretty sure that it is,

194
00:09:57,864 --> 00:10:02,996
Andy Keener has cost New
Amsterdam $1.4 million this year.

195
00:10:05,705 --> 00:10:08,140
And we haven't done
a thing to help him.

196
00:10:12,412 --> 00:10:17,043
Andy Keener has rung up over $1
million in charges here at New Amsterdam.

197
00:10:17,150 --> 00:10:20,177
That is enough for
50,000 prenatal visits,

198
00:10:20,253 --> 00:10:24,850
two liver transplants, or,
you know, one NBA contract.

199
00:10:24,924 --> 00:10:28,019
How do we lower this
number right there?

200
00:10:31,197 --> 00:10:32,324
Don't look at me.

201
00:10:32,398 --> 00:10:34,743
Well, he's had over 30 visits
and three surgeries for a foot ulcer.

202
00:10:34,767 --> 00:10:37,396
He walks around all day. He
can't keep his foot elevated.

203
00:10:37,504 --> 00:10:39,905
Look, bandages fall off,
antibiotic creams get lost.

204
00:10:40,006 --> 00:10:43,067
Okay, Bloom. ED's number one on
the hospital encounters hit parade.

205
00:10:43,209 --> 00:10:46,179
My ED is open 24/7,
so if he wants to get out

206
00:10:46,246 --> 00:10:49,080
of the rain, or snow, or
sun, or get a hot meal, then...

207
00:10:49,182 --> 00:10:54,553
Got it. Neurology. 10 EEGs and
18 head CT scans this year alone.

208
00:10:54,621 --> 00:10:56,180
All indicated and necessary.

209
00:10:56,256 --> 00:10:59,090
Andy falls, and gets beaten
up, and has a withdrawal seizure.

210
00:10:59,192 --> 00:11:02,185
EMTs bring him in and we
give him the same evaluation

211
00:11:02,262 --> 00:11:03,855
we would give to anyone else.

212
00:11:03,930 --> 00:11:06,729
Yeah, Helen, you can't tell me that
all these biopsies were necessary.

213
00:11:06,799 --> 00:11:08,677
Well, if we don't have
a patient's family history

214
00:11:08,701 --> 00:11:10,567
then all concerns have
to be taken seriously.

215
00:11:10,637 --> 00:11:13,698
Psychiatry, help me out. There's
gotta be a way to save a dollar.

216
00:11:13,773 --> 00:11:15,435
Just one dollar.

217
00:11:15,542 --> 00:11:18,740
Uh, no. No can do, Doc. Andy
suffers from PTSD and depression.

218
00:11:18,811 --> 00:11:21,906
An abusive childhood will do that to
you. Not to mention, he is an alcoholic.

219
00:11:21,981 --> 00:11:23,711
Multiple detox stays.

220
00:11:23,883 --> 00:11:25,977
Okay, so what
everyone is telling me

221
00:11:26,085 --> 00:11:30,489
is that not only was there no
way to avoid spending $1.4 million

222
00:11:30,590 --> 00:11:33,150
on Andy Keener this year,
but apparently there's no way

223
00:11:33,259 --> 00:11:38,891
to avoid spending another $1.4
million on Andy Keener next year?

224
00:11:42,569 --> 00:11:45,095
Yes? Yes, I was
hoping to meet Earl.

225
00:11:45,738 --> 00:11:47,604
Is Earl here? Is
he coming later?

226
00:11:47,674 --> 00:11:48,733
Not here, okay.

227
00:11:48,808 --> 00:11:51,175
Hey, Max, hold up. You
got a fix for Andy Keener?

228
00:11:51,277 --> 00:11:55,112
No, apparently I missed the Solve-America's-Homeless-
Epidemic class in med school.

229
00:11:55,181 --> 00:11:56,615
Fair enough. All right, so, uh,

230
00:11:56,683 --> 00:11:59,676
look, a reporter from <i>The New
England Cardiothoracic Journal</i>

231
00:11:59,786 --> 00:12:00,981
dug up some dirt on me.

232
00:12:01,087 --> 00:12:04,148
Some dirt that... That
could embarrass the hospital.

233
00:12:04,257 --> 00:12:06,158
Define "dirt."

234
00:12:06,259 --> 00:12:09,252
Ten years ago I was
arrested and, um,

235
00:12:09,629 --> 00:12:11,495
she wants to print my mug shot.

236
00:12:12,165 --> 00:12:13,861
Every time I think
this is dead and buried

237
00:12:13,967 --> 00:12:15,663
it just keeps popping
back up in my life,

238
00:12:15,802 --> 00:12:18,772
and I never wanted to be a
burden to you or this hospital.

239
00:12:18,838 --> 00:12:20,170
You're not.

240
00:12:20,506 --> 00:12:22,270
You wanna tell me what happened?

241
00:12:22,342 --> 00:12:23,810
Do I have to?

242
00:12:23,876 --> 00:12:27,142
Well, if I knew the story,
would I trust you less?

243
00:12:27,280 --> 00:12:28,339
No.

244
00:12:28,448 --> 00:12:30,328
Would it make me think
less of you as a surgeon?

245
00:12:30,516 --> 00:12:31,677
No.

246
00:12:31,784 --> 00:12:34,549
Then I don't need to know,
and neither does anybody else.

247
00:12:36,689 --> 00:12:38,658
I just don't want anyone
to think less of me.

