00:25:06,372 --> 00:25:09,069
I can make it so this Penny
Atwater can't find a job

500
00:25:09,141 --> 00:25:11,576
at <i>The New England
Journal of Trout Fishing.</i>

501
00:25:11,777 --> 00:25:13,245
Damn, you're good.

502
00:25:13,912 --> 00:25:15,642
It's just so typical.

503
00:25:16,048 --> 00:25:18,449
It's like if you're
African-American

504
00:25:18,550 --> 00:25:20,143
and you're exemplary,

505
00:25:20,252 --> 00:25:22,084
they're always
looking for a catch.

506
00:25:24,223 --> 00:25:25,885
I just want my nephew

507
00:25:26,458 --> 00:25:31,089
to know that you can be exemplary
without a catch, you know?

508
00:25:32,731 --> 00:25:34,962
As your legal representation,

509
00:25:35,067 --> 00:25:36,763
I can make this all go away.

510
00:25:39,972 --> 00:25:41,668
But as your girlfriend,

511
00:25:42,274 --> 00:25:44,641
I think you should
own your story.

512
00:25:45,411 --> 00:25:47,744
Not in spite of your nephew.

513
00:25:47,813 --> 00:25:49,748
Because of your nephew.

514
00:25:50,416 --> 00:25:52,351
He should know the truth.

515
00:25:53,685 --> 00:25:55,119
All of it.

516
00:26:05,831 --> 00:26:07,299
Well,

517
00:26:08,200 --> 00:26:09,691
here we are.

518
00:26:18,544 --> 00:26:21,480
It's safe to come
all the way in.

519
00:26:38,230 --> 00:26:39,892
Well, will you look at that?

520
00:26:39,998 --> 00:26:42,058
Stove works. Good to know.

521
00:26:44,369 --> 00:26:46,736
I haven't made
myself a cup of coffee

522
00:26:47,506 --> 00:26:48,667
in decades.

523
00:26:51,043 --> 00:26:54,207
Look, Andy, uh, I know
this place isn't much but...

524
00:26:54,313 --> 00:26:55,576
No.

525
00:26:56,048 --> 00:26:58,916
It's an awful lot, Dr. Goodwin.

526
00:27:01,487 --> 00:27:03,649
When do I need
to be out of here?

527
00:27:04,156 --> 00:27:07,024
No, uh, this isn't temporary.

528
00:27:07,092 --> 00:27:10,221
Andy, this place is yours
as long as you want it.

529
00:27:10,329 --> 00:27:12,355
Just no pets.

530
00:27:12,564 --> 00:27:15,261
Other than that,
you make the rules.

531
00:27:16,034 --> 00:27:18,230
All of this is mine?

532
00:27:22,875 --> 00:27:25,071
Welcome home, Andy.

533
00:27:48,800 --> 00:27:50,063
Floyd?

534
00:27:50,702 --> 00:27:52,034
You wanna begin?

535
00:27:56,475 --> 00:27:57,909
Yeah.

536
00:28:02,214 --> 00:28:03,807
It was, uh...

537
00:28:04,116 --> 00:28:05,584
It was 2008.

538
00:28:06,318 --> 00:28:07,752
Election night.

539
00:28:09,221 --> 00:28:11,952
And we're having this big party

540
00:28:12,791 --> 00:28:15,784
out in Connecticut where I
was interning at a hospital.

541
00:28:16,161 --> 00:28:17,720
And, uh,

542
00:28:18,397 --> 00:28:19,797
it was electric.

543
00:28:20,732 --> 00:28:25,295
I remember I never felt so,
uh, empowered, you know?

544
00:28:25,404 --> 00:28:26,428
So present.

545
00:28:26,905 --> 00:28:29,841
So American.

546
00:28:30,509 --> 00:28:32,273
I felt invincible and

547
00:28:32,611 --> 00:28:35,137
I was on my way home
back to my apartment,

548
00:28:35,247 --> 00:28:39,309
and I remember I rolled the windows
down so that I could feel that cool breeze.

549
00:28:39,785 --> 00:28:41,185
And the empty road.

550
00:28:41,286 --> 00:28:42,686
And then

551
00:28:43,121 --> 00:28:44,612
flashing red lights.

552
00:28:45,324 --> 00:28:46,622
Siren.

553
00:28:46,692 --> 00:28:48,285
I was getting pulled over.

554
00:28:48,527 --> 00:28:51,656
And I checked the speedometer,
only three miles over the speed limit.

555
00:28:52,831 --> 00:28:54,766
Officer asked me to step out.

556
00:28:55,801 --> 00:28:57,497
Still had on my scrubs.

557
00:28:57,936 --> 00:29:01,805
Showed him my hospital
badge but he didn't like my tone.

558
00:29:02,774 --> 00:29:04,834
And I begged him.

559
00:29:05,210 --> 00:29:06,974
I begged him to
just give me a ticket.

560
00:29:07,312 --> 00:29:08,439
Nope.

561
00:29:08,647 --> 00:29:11,173
There I was, face-down
on my own hood

562
00:29:11,283 --> 00:29:13,809
with my arms cuffed
behind my back

563
00:29:14,186 --> 00:29:17,281
on a night that started
out at my dream internship

564
00:29:17,356 --> 00:29:21,020
celebrating this newfound
hope for America.

565
00:29:24,162 --> 00:29:27,326
Ended with me in a holding
cell, stripped of my dignity.

566
00:29:28,500 --> 00:29:32,961
Waiting for my sister to catch the
next train up, so she could bail me out.

567
00:29:34,740 --> 00:29:37,175
Not even a Morehouse
College license plate

568
00:29:37,242 --> 00:29:39,541
or a Yale Med School
bumper sticker could save me.

569
00:29:39,645 --> 00:29:41,671
No, a mug shot,

570
00:29:42,247 --> 00:29:44,011
that you found,

571
00:29:44,583 --> 00:29:47,052
as a lifelong souvenir.

572
00:29:48,420 --> 00:29:50,531
You know, I was ashamed
of that night for a long time.

573
00:29:50,555 --> 00:29:53,218
That's why I...
That's why I buried it.

574
00:29:53,925 --> 00:29:56,861
You know, that's why I
tried to forget all about it.

575
00:29:56,928 --> 00:29:59,830
I mean, the fact that you
were so eager to shoehorn it

576
00:29:59,898 --> 00:30:02,766
into an article that purports
to celebrate a black doctor,

577
00:30:02,868 --> 00:30:05,064
I mean...

578
00:30:05,237 --> 00:30:07,206
That says very little about me.

579
00:30:11,677 --> 00:30:14,408
I'm a good surgeon.

580
00:30:15,280 --> 00:30:16,509
Period.

581
00:30:18,917 --> 00:30:20,510
That's your story.

582
00:30:28,293 --> 00:30:29,556
What are you doing here?

583
00:30:29,628 --> 00:30:30,926
Can't I just stop by to say hi?

584
00:30:31,029 --> 00:30:32,622
Any time. All the time.

585
00:30:32,798 --> 00:30:34,266
Would you like to go for dinner?

586
00:30:34,366 --> 00:30:36,528
There's a nice Indian
restaurant down the street.

587
00:30:36,802 --> 00:30:38,802
The food tastes exactly
like your mother's cooking.

588
00:30:39,604 --> 00:30:43,632
Actually, I have
plans with Ella.

589
00:30:45,077 --> 00:30:46,101
Ella?

590
00:30:46,211 --> 00:30:48,203
Turns out we have
the same taste in music.

591
00:30:48,914 --> 00:30:50,314
Weird, right?

592
00:30:52,084 --> 00:30:53,382
Where are you going?

593
00:30:53,452 --> 00:30:54,784
We're gonna go
see this band play.

594
00:30:55,153 --> 00:30:57,565
The bassist is a friend of mine.
We used to jam together a lot.

595
00:30:57,589 --> 00:30:59,455
He was gonna help
me with the demo.

596
00:31:01,226 --> 00:31:02,319
Okay.

597
00:31:02,427 --> 00:31:03,759
Anyway,

598
00:31:04,463 --> 00:31:06,227
thanks for introducing us.

599
00:31:20,779 --> 00:31:22,975
You paged? BLOOM: I did.

600
00:31:23,081 --> 00:31:24,140
What happened?

601
00:31:24,516 --> 00:31:27,145
Uh, he says he fell off a
ladder and hit his head.

602
00:31:29,855 --> 00:31:32,586
Make that 1.5 million.

603
00:31:33,959 --> 00:31:35,154
Hey.

604
00:31:35,260 --> 00:31:38,662
Hey, uh, so can we please go
somewhere not healthy, for once?

605
00:31:38,764 --> 00:31:40,289
I mean, I actually
think I hate salad.

606
00:31:40,365 --> 00:31:41,663
Uh, Dr. Bloom?

607
00:31:41,767 --> 00:31:44,862
Can I ask you to take a quick
look at a patient in Bay 4?

608
00:31:44,970 --> 00:31:46,268
So close.

609
00:31:46,338 --> 00:31:47,772
Okay, um, I'm
gonna be right back.

610
00:31:47,839 --> 00:31:50,365
Your job is to Google dive bars.

611
00:31:50,709 --> 00:31:52,837
I want a giant,
disgusting burger.

612
00:31:52,944 --> 00:31:54,139
Ew.

613
00:32:32,918 --> 00:32:35,183
Lauren.

614
00:32:37,055 --> 00:32:38,318
Lauren!

615
00:33:10,856 --> 00:33:12,256
You're not real.

616
00:33:12,791 --> 00:33:14,123
You're not real.

617
00:34:33,471 --> 00:34:35,030
Buddy, you need a hand?

618
00:34:35,140 --> 00:34:37,166
You know what?

619
00:34:37,609 --> 00:34:39,441
That'd be awesome, thanks.

620
00:34:46,051 --> 00:34:47,781
All right, thanks, man.

621
00:34:47,852 --> 00:34:50,378
You should really go see a
doctor, man. That's a good idea.

622
00:35:02,033 --> 00:35:03,194
Max.

623
00:35:03,902 --> 00:35:05,734
Where are you? <i>33rd and Park.</i>

624
00:35:06,538 --> 00:35:07,870
I don't think I can make it.

625
00:35:08,573 --> 00:35:10,474
Stay there, I'm coming to you.

626
00:35:16,648 --> 00:35:18,344
I don't understand.

627
00:35:18,416 --> 00:35:20,908
Well, it's, um... It's
an agricultural co-op.

628
00:35:21,386 --> 00:35:22,979
It's not a hospital.

629
00:35:23,688 --> 00:35:25,350
No, it's not.

630
00:35:27,525 --> 00:35:29,892
What kind of medicine
do they practice there?

631
00:35:29,995 --> 00:35:31,258
None.

632
00:35:31,663 --> 00:35:33,359
They don't practice
medicine there.

633
00:35:33,865 --> 00:35:35,094
That's the point.

634
00:35:37,202 --> 00:35:42,231
You're suggesting I... I
send my son away without me

635
00:35:43,041 --> 00:35:44,600
to a farm?

636
00:35:45,176 --> 00:35:48,078
To a place where they
claim the way to fix him

637
00:35:48,179 --> 00:35:50,341
is to pretend
that he's not sick?

638
00:35:51,449 --> 00:35:56,080
You know, Hector, one of the keys to
avoiding relapse in delusional disorders

639
00:35:56,187 --> 00:35:57,587
is environment.

640
00:35:57,789 --> 00:36:00,953
Plain and simple. And
Tony's current environment,

641
00:36:02,761 --> 00:36:05,731
it's not helping. You know?

642
00:36:05,797 --> 00:36:07,561
You mean me?

643
00:36:08,566 --> 00:36:10,057
And me.

644
00:36:10,535 --> 00:36:12,197
And this hospital.

645
00:36:14,773 --> 00:36:15,900
That...

646
00:36:15,974 --> 00:36:17,533
That boy is the
pride of my life.

647
00:36:17,609 --> 00:36:18,633
I know.

648
00:36:19,778 --> 00:36:21,212
He needs his father.

649
00:36:21,279 --> 00:36:23,475
Someone who will... loves him.

650
00:36:23,782 --> 00:36:25,648
Who will run
through walls for him.

651
00:36:25,750 --> 00:36:27,480
No, no, no.
Listen, listen, listen.

652
00:36:27,585 --> 00:36:29,611
You're trying to fix him.

653
00:36:31,623 --> 00:36:33,615
We're all trying to fix him.

654
00:36:34,225 --> 00:36:39,789
And on a very deep,
profound level, Tony feels that.

655
00:36:40,899 --> 00:36:43,459
He knows it, and it's
making him worse.

656
00:36:43,935 --> 00:36:46,336
This place will
accept him as he is.

657
00:36:47,605 --> 00:36:49,096
You're telling me

658
00:36:49,941 --> 00:36:52,240
to stop trying to
make him better?

659
00:36:53,611 --> 00:36:55,307
To not be his father?

660
00:36:56,915 --> 00:36:58,611
You told me

661
00:36:59,017 --> 00:37:00,610
that to help Tony,

662
00:37:01,319 --> 00:37:04,016
you'd be willing to
risk losing some of him.

663
00:37:08,159 --> 00:37:10,094
This is how you do that.

664
00:37:26,811 --> 00:37:28,302
Andy?

665
00:37:31,382 --> 00:37:34,113
You gonna take
away my apartment?

666
00:37:34,185 --> 00:37:35,346
No.

667
00:37:37,055 --> 00:37:38,546
I don't know what to do.

668
00:37:40,458 --> 00:37:43,724
I guess I just like it here.

669
00:37:45,830 --> 00:37:47,298
Think we're the only ones.

670
00:37:48,967 --> 00:37:51,698
You are always welcome here

671
00:37:52,303 --> 00:37:53,703
when you're sick.

672
00:37:54,139 --> 00:37:55,732
And when you're not sick,

673
00:37:55,840 --> 00:37:59,402
we have a lot of people
that we have to take care of,

674
00:37:59,511 --> 00:38:02,140
and that's just the
way it has to be.

675
00:38:02,714 --> 00:38:04,205
I'll... I'll leave.

676
00:38:04,315 --> 00:38:05,806
No problem.

677
00:38:05,884 --> 00:38:07,147
Excuse me?

678
00:38:07,552 --> 00:38:09,352
Sorry, does anyone know
how to get to the ICU?

679
00:38:09,420 --> 00:38:12,857
Oh, dude, you can't get to
the 12th floor from this building.

680
00:38:12,924 --> 00:38:15,519
You gotta take the
elevator to the 3rd floor,

681
00:38:15,593 --> 00:38:18,028
then take the
breezeway to Harriman.

682
00:38:18,096 --> 00:38:21,066
Then you take the second
set of elevators to 12.

683
00:38:21,166 --> 00:38:22,725
Then you walk to
the end of the hall.

684
00:38:22,834 --> 00:38:24,860
Thanks, man. You're a lifesaver.

685
00:38:26,070 --> 00:38:27,368
Andy...

686
00:38:28,506 --> 00:38:30,668
Do you know how to get
to the Oncology Ward?

687
00:38:31,109 --> 00:38:35,342
Of course, I've had many the
nonexistent tumor examined there.

688
00:38:35,413 --> 00:38:37,575
How would you like to start
paying off that apartment?

689
00:38:38,516 --> 00:38:39,745
How?

690
00:38:40,218 --> 00:38:42,881
By spending a little more
time at New Amsterdam.

691
00:38:45,757 --> 00:38:47,089
Hey, champ.

692
00:38:47,192 --> 00:38:48,888
You got time to
rap for a minute?

693
00:38:51,529 --> 00:38:53,760
I got something to tell you.

694
00:38:54,899 --> 00:38:58,802
And I'm hoping you
can still be proud of me.

695
00:39:03,107 --> 00:39:09,741
<i>All inside our
Amsterdam she hides</i>

696
00:39:12,483 --> 00:39:15,578
<i>Watery-eyed</i>

697
00:39:15,954 --> 00:39:17,980
I... I can draw there?

698
00:39:19,891 --> 00:39:22,417
You can draw and paint

699
00:39:22,894 --> 00:39:24,419
and just be you.

700
00:39:27,632 --> 00:39:29,157
If you want, Tony.

701
00:39:29,634 --> 00:39:33,162
If it'll make you
happy, I'll let you go.

702
00:39:33,338 --> 00:39:36,240
<i>Oh, silhouette</i>

703
00:39:37,141 --> 00:39:40,339
<i>She's growing tall and fine</i>

704
00:39:42,347 --> 00:39:46,478
<i>She's got my back</i>

705
00:39:46,584 --> 00:39:50,749
<i>She'll follow me
down every street</i>

706
00:39:51,322 --> 00:39:54,952
<i>No matter what my crime</i>

707
00:39:55,026 --> 00:39:56,324
Lauren.

708
00:40:16,614 --> 00:40:18,446
Done enough good for one day?

709
00:40:21,019 --> 00:40:22,681
Think I'm gonna puke.

710
00:40:23,221 --> 00:40:25,053
We paid enough for those chairs.

711
00:40:25,156 --> 00:40:29,389
I think that our medical director
deserves to try them out sometime.

712
00:40:32,830 --> 00:40:34,856
I don't want
everyone to see me so

713
00:40:36,668 --> 00:40:38,159
weak.

714
00:40:38,703 --> 00:40:39,898
You know?

715
00:40:40,371 --> 00:40:42,465
It's why I can't
let Georgia come.

716
00:40:46,477 --> 00:40:48,207
Why I can't sit in that chair.

717
00:40:50,481 --> 00:40:52,382
Everybody's gonna see me.

718
00:40:59,090 --> 00:41:00,683
The answer's yes, Max.

719
00:41:03,528 --> 00:41:04,996
I'll be your deputy.

720
00:41:06,731 --> 00:41:08,393
But you... Go.

721
00:41:08,499 --> 00:41:09,762
Be weak.

722
00:41:10,268 --> 00:41:11,600
Sit.

723
00:41:13,438 --> 00:41:14,701
I won't watch.

724
00:41:36,694 --> 00:41:38,060
Millie.

725
00:41:38,429 --> 00:41:40,523
Glaciers are moving.
Children are being born.

726
00:41:40,598 --> 00:41:42,294
Can you shuffle any faster?

727
00:41:43,601 --> 00:41:46,799
I... I think I just went from a
stage three to a stage four.

728
00:41:46,904 --> 00:41:49,135
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

729
00:41:49,741 --> 00:41:51,232
Room for a fourth?

730
00:41:51,976 --> 00:41:54,309
Yeah, always. Unfortunately.

731
00:41:54,479 --> 00:41:55,811
Loving your slipper game, dude.

732
00:41:55,913 --> 00:41:57,142
Oh, yeah, thanks.

733
00:41:57,248 --> 00:41:59,479
I'm, uh, feeling
pretty good about it.

734
00:41:59,951 --> 00:42:02,978
Those are pretty sharp yourself.

735
00:42:04,555 --> 00:42:09,152
Okay, so, uh, these are mine,
I take it. Whose are those?

736
00:42:09,260 --> 00:42:11,058
Those are Stevie's.

737
00:42:11,129 --> 00:42:12,961
Our old fourth.

738
00:42:13,164 --> 00:42:15,099
We always deal him in.

739
00:42:15,900 --> 00:42:17,163
Hmm.

740
00:42:17,268 --> 00:42:19,328
You know how to
play euchre, Max?

741
00:42:20,104 --> 00:42:21,436
Uh...

742
00:42:21,506 --> 00:42:22,838
I'll catch on.
